# InverBrass Delivery Standards

Apply these standards whenever implementing, modifying or delivering software.

---

# Delivery Philosophy

Deliver software incrementally.

Every delivery should:

- Add measurable business value.
- Maintain platform stability.
- Preserve existing functionality.
- Improve overall platform quality.

Avoid large, uncontrolled changes.

---

# Build Pack Driven Development

Development is organized around approved Build Packs.

Always:

- Identify the active Build Pack.
- Implement only the approved scope.
- Complete one Build Pack before starting another unless explicitly instructed.

Do not introduce functionality from future Build Packs.

---

# Scope Control

Remain within the requested scope.

Avoid:

- Scope creep.
- Gold plating.
- Premature optimization.
- Unrequested features.

Recommend future enhancements separately.

---

# Source Control

Use Git for version control.

Commit changes that are:

- Small
- Logical
- Complete
- Traceable

Avoid large mixed-purpose commits.

---

# Commit Messages

Write meaningful commit messages.

Prefer:

- feat:
- fix:
- refactor:
- docs:
- test:
- chore:

Explain the business purpose where appropriate.

---

# Branching

Keep work isolated.

Do not merge incomplete functionality into the main branch.

Ensure branches remain synchronized with the latest approved baseline.

---

# Pull Requests

Before requesting review:

- Verify build success.
- Verify tests pass.
- Verify documentation is updated where required.
- Verify scope matches the approved Build Pack.

---

# Code Reviews

Every review should verify:

- Functional correctness.
- Architecture compliance.
- Security.
- Performance.
- Maintainability.
- Code readability.
- Test coverage.

Review quality is more important than review speed.

---

# Continuous Improvement

Each implementation should improve the platform by:

- Reducing duplication.
- Increasing reuse.
- Improving readability.
- Simplifying maintenance.
- Strengthening consistency.

Leave the codebase better than it was found.

---

# Release Readiness

Before considering a feature ready for release:

- Functional Requirements implemented.
- Business Rules implemented.
- Acceptance Criteria satisfied.
- Security verified.
- Quality checks completed.
- Documentation updated.
- No critical defects remain.

---

# Deployment Readiness

Software should be deployable at any time.

Avoid:

- Manual deployment dependencies.
- Environment-specific code.
- Hardcoded configuration.

Configuration should be externalized.

---

# Configuration Management

Separate:

- Configuration
- Secrets
- Code
- Environment-specific settings

Never hardcode deployment values.

---

# Rollback Readiness

Design deployments so they can be safely rolled back if necessary.

Avoid irreversible deployment steps.

---

# Documentation

Keep documentation synchronized with implementation.

Update documentation whenever:

- Features change.
- Configuration changes.
- Deployment processes change.
- Operational procedures change.

---

# Engineering Principles

Successful delivery is measured by:

- Predictability.
- Stability.
- Traceability.
- Maintainability.
- Business value.

Deliver software that the business can confidently adopt in production.
